%text Best if we just took some examples before reading any definitions Given a set $A = \left\lbrace 1,2,3\right\rbrace$, let us define the following relations % \begin{align} \begin{tabular}{NNN}
\hline & \text{Recipe} & \text{Will give} \\ \hline \small{R_1} & \small{\left\lbrace (a,b): a \leq b\right\rbrace} & \small{\lbrace (1,1),(1,2),(1,3),(2,2),(2,3),(3,3)\rbrace} \\ \hline \small{R_2} & \small{\left\lbrace (a,b): a = b \right\rbrace} & \small{\left\lbrace (1,1),(2,2), (3,3)\right\rbrace} \\ \hline \small{R_3} & \small{\left\lbrace (a,b): a \geq b\right\rbrace} & \small{\lbrace (1,1),(2,1),(2,2),(3,1),(3,2),(3,3)\rbrace} \\ \hline \end{tabular} \end{align} %text The three relations have also been classified below. As you read the table, remember the "recipes" we defined above % \begin{align} \begin{tabular}{lMNNN}
\hline \text{Type} & \text{Meaning} & R_1 & R_2 & R_3 \\ \hline \text{Reflexive} & (a,a)\in R\text{ for all } a & \checkmark & \checkmark & \checkmark \\ \hline \text{Symmetric} & (a,b)\in R\implies (b,a)\in R & X & \checkmark & X \\ \hline \text{Transitive} & (a,b), (b,c)\in R \implies (a,c)\in R & \checkmark & \checkmark & \checkmark \\ \hline \text{Equivalent} & \text{Is all three of the above} & X & \checkmark & X \\ \hline \end{tabular} \end{align} %text Note that these are \underline\text{not either-or} conditions A relation can be transitive but not reflexive or reflexive but not symmetric. It comes down to what the relation is%
